{"id": 7906, "source": "pestle", "subject": "chemistry", "course": null, "level": "SL", "paper": "1", "year": "2019", "session": "19N", "subtopic": "6-1-collision-theory-and-rates-of-reaction", "title": "19N.1.SL.TZ0.18", "topic_id": "6", "source_url": "https://pestle.pages.dev/app/", "question_html": "<div class=\"question\">\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">The graph shows the Maxwell–Boltzmann energy distribution curve for a given gas at a certain temperature.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"/></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">How will the curve change if the temperature of the gas is increased, while other conditions remain constant?</span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A.  The maximum is higher and to the left of A.<br/></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">B.  The maximum is higher and to the right of A.<br/></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">C.  The maximum is lower and to the right of A.<br/></span></span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">D.  The maximum is lower and to the left of A.</span></span></p>\n</div>", "solution_html": "<div class=\"question\">\n<p>C</p>\n</div>", "examiners_html": "<div class=\"question\">\n[N/A]\n</div>"}